Food journals can be helpful for monitoring progress. This is a food journal after running a food sensitivity on one of my clients. The comment: “I don’t feel full/still feel hungry…” is a common comment after eliminating food sensitivities. As inflammation in the gut decreases, the end result is less bloat. However, many clients interpret this as NOT being full. It’s important to recognize this change and know the threshold of fullness will be less. So make sure to do the following to be mindful of the new threshold. 

1. Chew 40 times per mouthful. 
2. Eat PFF (protein, fats & fiber).

These are 2 foundational principles to slow digestion and to feel satiated.

#robertyang #robyang #pff #eatwelltofeelwell #breathe #stress #stressrelief #breathwork #destress

Eating a PFF (protein, fat, & fiber) breakfast establishes stable blood sugar and creates the 2nd meal phenomenon which reduces blood glucose after lunch. This ensures an environment leading to stable blood sugar and energy. Thus no need for nap 😴 time after lunch. 

The need for coffee ☕️ decreases when you eat breakfast. You’ll naturally need less coffee because breakfast stabilizes blood sugar and will not need the cortisol (aka caffeine) boost. 

As mentioned above, breakfast helps stabilize blood sugar. If you don’t eat breakfast or skip meals, the adrenals will produce cortisol to help manage blood sugar. If this is a pattern, cortisol levels may become chronically elevated and this shifts the autonomic nervous system to the sympathetic nervous system. This puts you into “fight or flight” mode and depresses melatonin output. Therefore impacting sleep quality and duration. Anecdotally, many of my clients find it odd that they began to sleep well after we change their diet and stabilize blood sugar. But it happens a lot!

How do I resolve my bloat? 

This is a very common question I receive daily. Bloat is very insidious. It may accumulate over time, but most people are not paying attention. Typically there’s a stressful event that may trigger the bloat in a person then they have significant symptoms. The resolution for bloat is multifactorial. There are many factors to consider such as mental/emotional stress, hypochlorhydria, SIBO, candida, dehydration, physical stress, hormonal dysfunction, sleep, blood sugar, dysregulation, toxins and many others. Addressing these issues in a timely and efficient manner is the key to resolving your bloat.

SIDE STEP UP:  The step up is a great unilateral lower body exercise. I use this Side Step Up variation as there is no cheating with the non-working leg. The load is only on the working leg as I tap the heal of the non-working leg. Make sure the knee is tracking with the second toe and the hips remain level to the ground. If you are unable to maintain the knee and hip position then the load is too great or the step is too high.
